# Modals (`App/`) — mandatory

Whenever you add or change **modal overlays** in `App/` (dialogs, confirmations, bottom sheets / action sheets shown as overlays, pickers, lightboxes, or any full-screen or partial-screen layer that blocks or sits above the main UI), you **MUST** open and manage them with **react-popup-manager**. **Do not** use any other pattern to show those overlays unless there is an explicit project exception.

## Opening modals (required)

- **MUST** register/show/dismiss modal content through **react-popup-manager** APIs and providers as documented for that library (single supported stack for popups).
- **MUST NOT** introduce parallel modal systems for the same use case.

## Data in / result out (required)

Call sites must not rely on ad-hoc callbacks alone for “what happened.” Overlay modals **MUST** follow a single **input / output** contract so callers can branch in one place.

### Input — `data`

- **MUST** pass all payload the modal needs to render or validate as a single **`data`** prop on the popup component (or the object you pass to `popupManager.open`, with a **`data`** field). Do not scatter unrelated top-level props for the same concern; extend `data` instead.
- Optional UI-only props (e.g. `title`) may exist alongside `data` when they are not part of the domain payload.
- **MUST NOT** pass domain **`on*`** callbacks into modal components (`onSubmit`, `onSelect`, `onConfirm`, etc.). Outcomes are communicated only through the **`Promise`** / **`onClose(result)`** contract (library `onClose` is the single exception for wiring).

### Output — resolved `Promise`

- The API that opens the modal (hook or helper) **MUST** return **`Promise<Result>`** where `Result` is **`T \| null \| undefined`** for that modal (or an equivalent union) so **`undefined` and `null` are distinguishable** from a real payload `T`.
- The promise **MUST** resolve **exactly once** when the overlay is fully dismissed, with one of these outcomes (callers **MUST** handle all three):

| Resolved value | Meaning |
|----------------|---------|
| **`undefined`** | User dismissed by **pressing outside** the sheet (backdrop tap / outside press), without committing. |
| **`null`** | User **canceled** via an explicit in-sheet control (e.g. close, back, “Cancel”) or ended the flow **without** a payload (“no data”). |
| **`T` (some value)** | User **committed**: Save, Confirm, picked a row, approved, etc. The value is the **result payload** (object, array, or primitive); callers inspect it to see what was chosen. |

- **MUST NOT** use `reject()` for normal dismissals; use the resolution values above. Reserve `reject` for true failures (e.g. internal errors) if needed, and document that separately.
- Wiring: implement the promise in the hook/helper (e.g. wrap `popupManager.open` and pass `onClose` / resolve callbacks into the modal props) so screens use `await openFooModal({ data })` and switch on `result === undefined`, `result === null`, or use the narrowed `T`.

### Legacy modals

- Existing modals that still use callback-only props should be migrated to this contract when touched; **new** modals and **new** open flows **MUST** implement the `data` + `Promise` pattern from the start.

## iOS sheet look and motion (required)

- **MUST** present overlay modals as an **iOS-style sheet**: the sheet **animates from the bottom** (slide / translate on show and hide), anchored to the safe area as appropriate.
- **MUST** use a **backdrop** over the underlying UI that **fades** (opacity animation) in and out together with the sheet; avoid a hard-cut dim with no transition.

## Sheet height and scrolling (required)

- **MUST** size the sheet so its **height follows the content** (intrinsic / shrink-wrap height): for short content, the sheet **must not** occupy a tall empty band or default to full-screen height.
- **MUST** make **long** content **scroll inside the sheet**: use **`ScrollView`**, **`FlatList`**, or **`SectionList`** (or an equivalent scroll container) for the body, with layout that **caps** sheet growth (e.g. **max height** or flex so the sheet stops growing) so overflow scrolls **within** the sheet, not off-screen.
- **MUST NOT** leave overflowing sheet content non-scrollable.

## Do not

- **Do not** use React Native’s **`<Modal>`** component as the primary way to show app modals.
- **Do not** use other modal, popup, or overlay manager libraries (or ad-hoc global `useState` + portal trees) to open the same class of UI.
- **Do not** wire “open modal” flows through navigation-only presentation (e.g. stack `presentation: 'modal'`) **when** the intent is a managed overlay popup; use **react-popup-manager** instead.

## Scope note

- This rule targets **overlay modals managed as popups**. It does not replace normal **screen** navigation; route screens stay under the app’s router rules (`app-screens-routing.mdc`). If something is clearly a **route screen**, follow routing rules; if it is clearly a **popup overlay**, it **must** go through **react-popup-manager**.
